Written 12:48 PM  Nov 14, 1997 by tomgray in igc:energy.news<br>
<br>
---------- &quot;Base Load Wind Plants&quot; ----------<br>
BASE LOAD WIND PLANTS POSSIBLE, RESEARCHER SAYS<br>
<br>
        Wind power plants can achieve capacity factors <br>
comparable to those of conventional fueled generating plants <br>
or even higher at a modest increase in cost of energy (COE), <br>
according to one researcher who has studied the issue closely, and the COE may even drop when the cost of transmitting the power is considered.<br>
<br>
    The capacity factor of a wind or other power plant is determined by comparing its actual electricity production <br>
with the amount it would produce if operated 100% of the <br>
time.  Because the wind is intermittent, the capacity factor <br>
of wind plants is typically rather low--25% to 35%, compared <br>
to levels of perhaps 70% for nuclear or fossil plants that can be fueled as required.<br>
<br>
    However, Alfred Cavallo, a physicist who previously worked at the Center for Energy and Environmental Systems (CEES) at Princeton University, points out that the capacity factor of a wind plant can be increased simply by &quot;oversizing&quot; it-- adding more individual turbines than are needed to comprise the plant's &quot;nameplate&quot; capacity. <br>
 For instance, a 50-MW wind plant might typically be made up of twenty-five  2 megawatt turbines.  But if more turbines are added and one continues to consider the facility as a 50-MW plant, its capacity factor will rise.  And this is true even if steps are taken to limit the facility's peak production to no more than 50 MW (i.e., making it a &quot;true&quot; 50-MW plant) by <br>
shutting down some turbines during infrequent periods of high winds.<br>
<br>
   However, since oversizing the wind plant does increase the cost of energy at the &quot;busbar&quot; (the point at which it connects to the utility transmission system), this ability to increase capacity factor is only mildly interesting to utilities, Cavallo says.  The key, he adds, is that a higher-capacity-factor wind plant can utilize transmission lines more efficiently, thereby reducing transmission expenses per unit of electricity delivered.  If the plant is properly sized, the drop in transmission costs is larger than the increase in the cost of the plant, and so the overall cost of energy delivered over the transmission line is reduced.<br>
<br>
  In a paper scheduled for publication in November in the Journal of Solar Energy Engineering, he writes, &quot;By better understanding the tradeoff between capacity factor and the cost of electricity a more intelligent choice can be made between these two parameters given other system constraints, such as storage system size and cost, transmission system charges, or other limitations.&quot;<br>
<br>
   As an example specifically designed to show how the <br>
economics of a higher-capacity wind plant could be beneficial, Cavallo examines the case of a 2,000-MW wind farm located in western Kansas that transmits power to load centers in California over transmission lines.  (In such a situation, the cost of transmission becomes a major consideration, and utilizing the transmission line efficiently becomes correspondingly desirable.)<br>
<br>
    Normally, Cavallo says, the wind farm would be sized so <br>
that its maximum output was the same as the transmission <br>
line's capacity--in this case, 2,000 MW.  This would require, for example, 1,000  2 megawatt turbines.  If the wind plant were located in an area with relatively high average winds, it could achieve a capacity factor of 36%.<br>
<br>
   However, if the number of turbines is increased to 1,400, the plant's capacity factor rises to 49%.  When transmission costs are taken into account, the overall cost of the wind-generated electricity from the plant, delivered to California, actually drops even though the oversized plant contains more than 40% more turbines.  A graph showing combined capital, O&amp;M, and transmission costs for the facility indicates that the best economics occur in a range between 40% and 60% capacity factors.  Above 60%, the increasing capital cost of the wind plant begins to overshadow the decreases in transmission cost (even though those decreases do still continue).  <br>
<br>
   According to Cavallo, consideration of higher-capacity-<br>
factor wind installations will become necessary if wind energy development in the Great Plains becomes substantial in size: <br>
<br>
   &quot;The somewhat surprising and counter-intuitive result that wind-transmission systems can have a capacity factor of over 60% without an economic penalty and without storage is a consequence of the current development and design philosophy of wind turbines, which is to minimize the busbar cost of electricity [i.e., the cost of power generated by the turbine] with no consideration given to the wind turbine capacity factor.<br>
<br>
   &quot;This is a perfectly reasonable approach for present-day systems, which cover only a small fraction of utility demand and exploit resources close to demand centers.  In the future, as wind-generated electricity supplies a much more significant portion of total demand and more distant resources are utilized, system constraints must be taken into account and the delivered, not busbar, cost of electricity must be minimized.&quot;<br>
<br>
   Writes Cavallo, &quot;It is interesting to note that system <br>
capacity factors of over 60% are economically feasible with <br>
wind-only systems; this approaches the capacity factor of <br>
some nuclear power plants.&quot;  He adds, &quot;Storage can further <br>
increase the capacity factor of the system; for example, by <br>
combining a compressed-air energy storage [CAES] system with an oversized wind turbine array, intermittent wind energy <br>
can be transformed to a constantly-available power source <br>
for a cost premium of about 20% compared to a simple wind-<br>
only system.&quot;<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.idea.iastate.edu/isep/isep_background.asp" target="top">INFO ON CAES - CLICK HERE</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
 Cavallo examines the wind/CAES option in more detail in a paper published in 1995, also in the Journal of Solar Energy Engineering and also looking at a 2,000-MW facility in western Kansas.  (CAES involves the use of some fossil fuels--while wind-generated electricity can be used to run the air compressors, the energy is released from storage by burning natural gas or oil in combination with the compressed air to generate electricity.)  He writes, &quot;The levelized cost of delivered electricity for a wind-CAES-transmission system at a capacity factor of 90% is . . . about 4% higher than the cost . . . for the baseline system at a capacity factor of 36%.&quot;<br>
<br>
   Cavallo concludes:<br>
<br>
  &quot;Wind-generated electricity can be transformed fundamentally from an intermittent to a high-capacity factor <br>
or a baseload power supply.<br>
<br>
&quot;Wind farms with compressed-air energy storage systems with capacity factors greater than 90% (wind energy baseload systems) are economically attractive and technically feasible in the wind regime of the Great Plains.<br>
<br>
   &quot;If transmission costs are included, the delivered cost of electricity can be lower at higher system capacity factor.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Use of compressed-air energy storage systems reduces <br>
the cost of delivered electricity for very high-capacity-factor systems where transmission costs are significant.<br>
<br>
   &quot;This approach is ideally suited to the industrial-scale development of the wind resources of the Great Plains.  <br>
It is based on existing technologies whose cost and performance is well-documented.  In addition, it would make <br>
optimum use of transmission systems, which are expensive to <br>
build and difficult to site.&quot;<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=yales>yales</A> at: 5/16/03 10:46:01 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dio82@nuclearspace>dio82</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 6<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/27/04 10:17 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=163.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   re</span><hr size=1> This is the worst drivel I have read in long time!<br>
